:"okolo 1205","1184":"1184","About:1225":"okolo 1225","of Kells Parish, Wells, Kilkenny, Ireland":"Kells, County Kilkenny, Irsko","‏Eire":"Irsko","County Waterford, Eire":"County Waterford, Irsko","Ireland":"Irsko"},"da":{"circa 1205–":"omkring 1205–Afdød","1205–Male":"1205–Afdød","1210–Female":"1210–Afdød","1225–Male":"1225–Afdød","1184–1224":"1184–1224","1190–Female":"1190–Afdød","1190":"1190","before 1205":"før 1205","1205":"1205","before 1225":"før 1225","1225":"1225","1224":"1224","1210":"1210","circa 1205":"omkring 1205","1184":"1184","About:1225":"omkring 1225","of Kells Parish, Wells, Kilkenny, Ireland":"Kells, County Kilkenny, Irland","‏Eire":"Irland","County Waterford, Eire":"County Waterford, Irland","Ireland":"Irland"},"nl":{"circa 1205–":"circa 1205–Overleden","1205–Male":"1205–Overleden","1210–Female":"1210–Overleden","1225–Male":"1225–Overleden","1184–1224":"1184–1224","1190–Female":"1190–Overleden","1190":"1190","before 1205":"vóór 1205","1205":"1205","before 1225":"vóór 1225","1225":"1225","1224":"1224","1210":"1210","circa 1205":"circa 1205","1184":"1184","About:1225":"circa 1225","of Kells Parish, Wells, Kilkenny, Ireland":"Kells, County Kilkenny, Ierland","‏Eire":"Ierland","County Waterford, Eire":"County Waterford, Ierland","Ireland":"Ierland"},"en":{"circa 1205–":"about 1205–Deceased","1205–Male":"1205–Deceased","1210–Female":"1210–Deceased","1225–Male":"1225–Deceased","1184–1224":"1184–1224","1190–Female":"1190–Deceased","1190":"1190","before 1205":"before 1205","1205":"1205","before 1225":"before 1225","1225":"1225","1224":"1224","1210":"1210","circa 1205":"about 1205","1184":"1184","About:1225":"about 1225","of Kells Parish, Wells, Kilkenny, Ireland":"Kells, County Kilkenny, Ireland","‏Eire":"Ireland","County Waterford, Eire":"County Waterford, Ireland","Ireland":"Ireland","nameMeanings":[{"name":"le","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Vietnamese Thanh, Hung, Minh, Dung, Tuan, Hai, Hoa, Thuy, Son, Anh, Long, Hoang.  Chinese Hong, Sang, Chi, Dong, Tong, Lai, Hang, Man, Han, Ho, Phoung, Chan.  Korean Tam, Phong, Nam, Thai, Tuong, Chung, Thach, Tinh, Manh, Tham, Uyen, Vang.","Chinese: Mandarin form of the surname 樂, meaning ‘happiness’ in Chinese: from the first element of the personal name Le Fu (樂父), style name of Yan, son of the Duke Dai of Song (ruler of the state of Song, reigned 799–766  BC ). Yan's grandson Le Ju (樂莒) inherited Le (樂) as his surname.","Chinese: Mandarin form of the surname 勒: (i) from the second element of the placename Shu-Le (疏勒), an ancient state (located in present-day Xinjiang Uyghur autonomous region) during the Western Han dynasty (206  BC –25  AD ). (ii) a surname near the Bohai Sea region during the Han dynasty (206  BC –220  AD ). (iii) a surname traced back to the Hun ethnic group in northern China during the Jin dynasty (265–420  AD )."],"variants":[{"name":"Yue","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Chinese: Chi, Feng, Gang, Wei, Chun, Guo, Jin, Kin, Ping, Yan, Yun, Zhang, Chau, Du, Hau, Hung, My, Sau.","Chinese:","Mandarin form of the surname 岳 (or 嶽), meaning ‘high mountain’ in Chinese: traced back to Si Yue (四岳 or 四嶽), said to be the title of an official post in charge of sacrificial rituals on the site of famous mountains during the reign of the legendary Emperor Yao (<i>c.</i> 24th century  BC ) and Emperor Shun (<i>c.</i> 23rd century  BC )."]},{"name":"Lok","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Chinese Ping, Tat, Wing, Ying Lin, Chi Ming, Ching Wah, Chun, Chung Man, Han, Kam, Kam Tim, Kin.","Chinese: Cantonese form of the surname 樂, see   Le   1.","Chinese: Cantonese form of the surnames 陸, 鹿, 逯 and 禄, see   Lu   5 and (7-9)."]},{"name":"Li","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Chinese Wei, Ming, Li, Jian, Hong, Yan, Ping, Jing, Yong, Ying, Hui, Jin, Min, Chung.","Chinese: Mandarin form of the surname 李, meaning ‘plum’: (i) said to have been adopted in place of the Chinese surname 理 (also pronounced Li; meaning ‘rules’ in Chinese) by Li Zhen (利貞), son of an official called Li Zheng (理徵) in the late Shang dynasty (1600–1046  BC ). It is said that Li Zhen's father incurred the displeasure of King Zhou of Shang (died 1046  BC ) and Li Zhen fled to a wasteland area, where he survived on wild plums. After his return to civilization, he changed his surname to Li (李 ‘plum’), a word with the same pronunciation. The original surname, 理, is said to be from Li Guan (理官), the name of a post of officials in charge of legislation in ancient China. Li Er (李耳), also known as Lao Tzu or Lao Zi, traditionally regarded as the founder of Taoism, is believed to have been a descendant of Li Zhen. (ii) adopted as a surname by the Chi Li (叱李) family from the Xianbei ethnic group during the Northern Wei dynasty (386–534  AD ). (iii) in the early years of the Tang dynasty (618–907  AD ), sixteen high officials with different surnames were granted the surname Li (李), the surname of the royal family of the Tang dynasty, by Emperor Taizong of Tang (died 649  BC ), because of their contributions to the establishment of the Tang regime. (iv) the surname can also be traced back to several minority ethnic groups in ancient China.","Chinese: Mandarin form of the surname 黎, meaning ‘black’ or ‘multitude’ in ancient Chinese: (i) from Li (黎), the name of an ancient state (located in Changzhi in Shanxi province) during the Shang dynasty (1600–1046  BC ), which was annexed in the Western Zhou dynasty (1046–771  BC ) and later granted to Fengshu, also known as Li Hou (黎侯, 'Marquis Li'). (ii) adopted as a surname by the Su Li (素黎) family, members of the Xianbei ethnic group, during the Northern Wei dynasty (386–534  AD )."]}]},{"name":"Poher","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Fritz.","North German (also <b>Pöhler</b>):","topographic name for someone who lived by a muddy pool (see   Pohl  ), or a habitational name for someone from any of several places called Pohl, Pohle, or Pohla."],"variants":[{"name":"Pohl","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Kurt, Erwin, Otto, Wolfgang, Gerhard, Gunther, Hans, Horst, Manfred, Oskar, Claus, Dietrich.","German: topographic name from Middle Low German <i>pōl</i> ‘(muddy) pool, wetland’ (Low German <i>Pohl</i>), or a habitational name from any of several places called Pohl, Pohle, or Pohla.","German (<b>Pöhl</b>): see   Poehl  ."]},{"name":"Poehler","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Alfons, Dieter, Horst, Juergen, Otto.","North German (<b>Pöhler</b>):","topographic name for someone who lived by a muddy pool, from an agent noun derived from Middle Low German <i>pōl</i> ‘(muddy) pool’."]}]},{"name":"Benet","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["The normal medieval vernacular form of   Benedict  , borne by women as well as men in the past. Now sometimes used as an antiquarian revival, but more often a transferred use of the surname derived from the medieval given name."],"variants":[{"name":"Bennet","meanings":["Latin: From the Latin name Benedictus."]},{"name":"Benett","meanings":["See Bennet."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Benet le Poher was born about 1205, in County Waterford, Ireland, his father, Walter le Poher, was 22 and his mother, Feya d'Eincourt, was 11203. He married Margaret Le Grace before 1225, in Kells, County Kilkenny, Ireland. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died in Ireland."},"et":{"circa 1205–":"umbes 1205–Surnud","1205–Male":"1205–Surnud","1210–Female":"1210–Surnud","1225–Male":"1225–Surnud","1184–1224":"1184–1224","1190–Female":"1190–Surnud","1190":"1190","before 1205":"enne 1205","1205":"1205","before 1225":"enne 1225","1225":"1225","1224":"1224","1210":"1210","circa 1205":"umbes 1205","1184":"1184","About:1225":"umb